EMPLOYEE ENGAGEMENT SURVEY
Data Cleaning, Dashboard & Insights Report — Pierce County, WA
Data Source: Employee_Survey.xlsx (raw survey export)  •  Analytics Model: EMPLY_2.pbix (Power Query + Power BI dashboard)
1.  Executive Summary
This report documents the end-to-end journey of the Pierce County WA Employee Engagement Survey data from the raw, unprocessed export received from the survey platform, through the data-cleaning and transformation process applied in Power Query, to the final interactive Power BI dashboard used for reporting. It also summarizes the key workforce engagement insights the cleaned data reveals and the recommendations that follow from them.
The raw dataset contained 14,725 individual question-level responses submitted by employees across 20 departments, covering 10 core engagement questions. Before analysis, the data required correction of duplicate records, inconsistent question labels, unclassified job-role fields, and incomplete submissions. After cleaning, the dataset was modeled in Power BI and visualized in a single-page executive dashboard built around five headline KPIs, four supporting visuals, and three interactive filters.
Overall, the organization's engagement is moderately positive: 77.3% of valid responses were favorable (Agree/Strongly Agree) against 22.7% unfavorable, producing an average engagement score of 3.07 out of 4.0. The analysis also surfaces clear opportunities for improvement most notably in recognition, workplace connection, and accountability and identifies the Sheriff's Department as the area most in need of targeted engagement intervention.
2.  The Raw (Dirty) Dataset
The source file, Employee_Survey.xlsx, was received in "long" format: rather than one row per survey respondent, each row represents a single respondent's answer to a single question, so a fully-completed survey produces 10 rows. The workbook contained two sheets: the response data itself ("HR Survey Reponses") and an accompanying data dictionary.
2.1  Structure of the Raw Data
Field	Description
Response ID	Sequential ID identifying the survey submission a row belongs to
Status	Complete or Incomplete
Department	Respondent's department (20 distinct departments)
Director / Manager / Supervisor / Staff	Four separate binary (0/1) columns flagging the respondent's role level
Question	Full text of the survey question
Response	Numeric answer code (0–4)
Response Text	Text label for the answer (Not Applicable → Strongly Agree)
Table 1 — Raw data dictionary, as supplied with the source file
2.2  Data Quality Issues Identified
Profiling the 14,725-row raw file surfaced six distinct data-quality problems that had to be resolved before the data could be trusted for reporting:
#	Issue	Scale
1	Incomplete submissions — Response and Response Text left blank	135 rows (0.9%)
2	Exact duplicate rows (same respondent, question, and answer repeated)	15 rows
3	Question 7 recorded under two different wordings ("learn and grow" vs. "learn & grow")	962 vs. 509 rows
4	Question 10 recorded with a trailing whitespace variant, splitting it into two labels	1,454 vs. 22 rows
5	No standardized role/seniority field — role was spread across four separate binary columns	All 14,725 rows
6	No respondent classified into a role at all (all four role flags = 0)	10,572 rows (71.8%)
Table 2 — Data quality issues found during profiling of the raw dataset
Issues #3 and #4 are especially important because Power BI (and most BI tools) treats every distinct string as its own category  left unresolved, the dashboard would have reported 11 separate "questions" instead of 10, splitting the results for two questions in half and understating their true response volumes. Issue #6 (71.8% of respondents not classified into any role) is the most material limitation of the dataset and is carried forward as a caveat in the insights section of this report.
3.  Data Cleaning Process
Cleaning and transformation were performed in Power Query as part of the Power BI data model (EMPLY_2.pbix). The applied query steps were extracted directly from the model and are summarized below in the order they were executed.
Step	Power Query Action	Purpose
1	Promote Headers & Change Type	Correctly typed each column (IDs and role flags as whole numbers, Response as a number, remaining fields as text)
2	Fill Down on "Response Text"	Propagated the nearest valid answer label downward into blank cells left by incomplete submissions
3	Fill Up on "Response"	Propagated the nearest valid numeric answer code upward into blank Response cells
4	Added Column — "Role"	Collapsed the four binary Director/Manager/Supervisor/Staff columns into one readable category, defaulting to "Not Specified" when none were flagged
5	Added Column — "Question Shorts"	Mapped all 11 raw question-text variants to 10 standardized codes (Q1–Q10) using keyword matching, merging the Question 7 and Question 10 wording splits
6	Added Column — "Role Sort" (DAX)	Assigned a numeric sort order to the Role field (Staff → Not Specified → Supervisor → Manager → Director) so dashboard visuals display roles in a logical hierarchy
Table 3 — Transformation steps applied in Power Query, in execution order
3.1  Before vs. After Cleaning
Aspect	Raw Data	Cleaned Data
Row count	14,725	14,725 (unchanged — see note below)
Columns	10	13 (+ Role, Question Shorts, Role Sort)
Distinct question labels	11 (2 questions split by wording)	10 standardized question codes
Blank Response / Response Text	135 rows blank	0 rows blank (filled via Fill Down / Fill Up)
Role field	Spread across 4 binary columns	Single "Role" category field
