3.2  Residual Limitations Carried Into the Dashboard
Two items from the cleaning process are worth flagging transparently rather than glossing over:
•	Duplicates were not removed. The 15 exact duplicate rows identified in profiling remain in the data model and are not filtered out by any measure, so headline counts are very slightly inflated (well under 0.1% of the total).
•	The Fill Down / Fill Up approach imputes rather than removes incomplete answers. Because "Response Text" was filled downward and "Response" was filled upward independently, a small number of the 135 originally-incomplete rows (under 1% of the full dataset) ended up with a numeric code and a text label that don't correspond to the same answer. This does not materially affect the headline KPIs but means row-level detail for former "Incomplete" submissions should not be trusted in isolation.
•	The 71.8% of rows with no role classification ("Not Specified") could not be recovered through cleaning, since the underlying source data simply never captured that information for those respondents. This is a data-collection gap, not a cleaning-process gap, and is addressed in the recommendations.
