6.  Dashboard Insights
The charts below are reconstructed directly from the cleaned data model to walk through the same story the live Power BI dashboard tells.
6.1  Overall Sentiment
 
Figure 2 — Distribution of all 14,725 responses by answer category
Combined "Agree" and "Strongly Agree" responses account for 75.2% of all responses submitted (39.3% Agree + 35.9% Strongly Agree), against 22.2% unfavorable (14.9% Disagree + 7.3% Strongly Disagree) and 2.7% Not Applicable. This broadly positive skew is consistent with the 77.3% positive rate reported on the KPI card, which recalculates the same split after excluding Not Applicable answers.
6.2  Engagement by Question
 
Figure 3 — Average score by question (1 = Strongly Disagree, 4 = Strongly Agree)
Breaking the average score down by question reveals meaningful variation. Employees are most confident that they understand what's expected of them at work (Q1, 3.49) and that their supervisor cares about them personally (Q4, 3.29). Scores are weakest for having a best friend at work (Q6, 2.60), receiving recognition for good work in the last seven days (Q3, 2.80), and feeling their supervisor holds people accountable for performance (Q8, 2.95) — all three sit below the 3.07 organizational average.
6.3  Engagement by Role
 
Figure 4 — Average score by role level
Engagement rises steadily with seniority: Staff score lowest at 2.97, followed by the unclassified "Not Specified" group at 3.03, then Supervisors (3.20), Managers (3.27), and Directors, who report the highest engagement at 3.37. This 0.40-point gap between Staff and Director-level employees is a classic front-line engagement gap and — combined with the fact that most "Not Specified" respondents are likely front-line employees who simply didn't self-identify a role — suggests the true gap between leadership and front-line staff may be even larger than the classified figures alone show.
6.4  Engagement by Department
 
Figure 5 — Average score by department, ranked lowest to highest
Department-level results show the widest spread in the dataset. The Sheriff's Department scores markedly lower than every other department, at 2.47 against an organization-wide average of 3.07 — a 0.60-point gap that flags it as the clearest priority for a focused engagement intervention. District Court (2.98) and Planning and Public Works (3.05) also sit at or below average. At the other end, Family Justice Center (3.62), Emergency Management (3.47), and Exec Office & Directors (3.44) report the strongest engagement, though the smallest departments (e.g., Family Justice Center, with only 40 total responses) should be read with caution given their limited sample size.
7.  Recommendations
7.1  Act on the Engagement Findings
•	Prioritize the Sheriff's Department for a targeted engagement review. Its score is the lowest in the county by a wide margin; given the operational and shift-work pressures common in law enforcement, a focused listening session or pulse survey would help isolate root causes before designing an intervention.
•	Strengthen recognition practices. Question 3 (recognition for good work) is one of the three lowest-scoring items  introduce lightweight, frequent recognition mechanisms (peer shout-outs, manager check-ins) rather than relying on annual reviews alone.
•	Invest in workplace connection. The lowest-scoring question overall, "I have a best friend at work," points to weak social cohesion in some teams; team-building activities and structured onboarding buddy programs can help, particularly in larger, dispersed departments.
•	Reinforce accountability for performance. With Q8 also below average, supervisors may benefit from training and clearer tools for setting and following up on performance expectations.
•	Close the staff-to-leadership engagement gap. Consider skip-level meetings and structured upward-feedback channels so front-line staff  the county's lowest-scoring group  have a direct line to leadership rather than relying solely on their immediate supervisor.
7.2  Improve Future Data Collection & Governance
•	Make role selection a required field in the survey instrument. With 71.8% of respondents currently unclassified, role-based analysis today rests on fewer than 3 in 10 responses  a mandatory single role-selector question would close this gap directly.
•	Replace free-text or re-typed question wording with a fixed question bank. The Question 7 and Question 10 wording splits in the raw data both stemmed from the question text being re-entered rather than pulled from a controlled list; locking question text at the source removes the need for downstream keyword-matching fixes.
•	Add duplicate-prevention logic (e.g., one-submission-per-employee-per-cycle) at the point of collection, and explicitly deduplicate on Response ID + Question during the load step going forward.
•	Reconsider how incomplete submissions are handled. Filling blank answers from adjacent rows is a reasonable stop-gap, but excluding incomplete submissions from the model entirely (or flagging them clearly to report users) would be a more transparent long-term approach.
8.  Conclusion
Pierce County's employee engagement data, once cleaned and modeled, tells a consistent and actionable story: engagement is moderately positive overall (77.3% favorable, average score 3.07 of 4.0), but the organization has clear, specific levers available to raise it further  chiefly recognition, workplace connection, accountability, and closing the gap between front-line staff and leadership. The Sheriff's Department stands out as the single highest-priority area for intervention. Addressing the data-collection gaps identified in this report, particularly mandatory role capture and controlled question wording, will make the next survey cycle materially easier to clean and more reliable to act on.

